    You probably wonder why you would make the Bessel correction. The reason is important. We will see that the main goal of statistics is to infer the underlying probability distribution of a collection of empirical observations. In other words, we have a lottery machine filled with many balls (population), but we only see a small sample of those balls, and our goal is to guess what the population looks like based on a small sample (see statistical inference).

    Background

    In statistics, the word â€œnormalâ€ does not mean â€œtypicalâ€. Instead, â€œnormalâ€ refers to a very important continuous distribution: the normal distribution. Normal distributions are important because random sums and random averages are approximately normal (see central limit theorem). For example, if you repeatedly roll 100 dice, taking the sum of each 100, those sums will be normally distributed (even though single rolls are discrete-uniformly distributed).

    A normal distribution has a bell-shaped density curve. The center and spread of the bell are dictated by two parameters: mean (Î¼\mu) and standard deviation (Ïƒ\sigma). The normal density curve is defined by the following equation: normal density as function of x=1Ïƒ2Ï€eâˆ’12(xâˆ’Î¼Ïƒ)2\text{normal density as function of x} = \frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^2} where Î¼\mu is the mean, Ïƒ\sigma is the standard deviation, Ï€\pi is the ratio of a circleâ€™s circumference to its diameter, and ee is Eulerâ€™s number.

    For the first exam, we are expected to know the empirical rule. We are going to round unconventionally, so for us it could be called the â€œ68-96-100 ruleâ€. It implies that in a normal distribution 68% of the measurements are within 1 standard deviation of the mean, 96% of the measurements are within 2 standard deviations of the mean, and 100% of the measurements are within 3 standard deviations of the mean.

    We can visualize the â€œ68-96-100â€ rule with a density curve. Notice the area of each region is shown, and you can estimate the areas by counting percentage boxes.
